	<article class="article ">
		<header class="block-content block-content-l1 block-content-center">
						<div class="block-content-header">
				<h6 class="b-content-section heading-square"><a href="/sections/essays-memoirs-true-stories">Essays, Memoirs, and True Stories</a></h6>
				<h1 class="block-content-title">A Sun Valentine</h1>

								<p class="block-content-subtitle subtitle">On Love And Relationship</p>
				
				<ul class="block-content-meta list-inline-border tiny"><li><a href="/issues/75">February 1982</a></li></ul>

			</div>

								</header>

				<div class="article-body link-text-wrap">
																		<p><em>There&rsquo;s a character in one of Kurt Vonnegut&rsquo;s novels who offers a piece of chocolate to anyone who&rsquo;s sad. Now, the scientists say there&rsquo;s a chemical in chocolate identical to something the brain produces when we&rsquo;re in love. Does chocolate make us feel in love, then, or ease a broken heart? Yoko Ono ate almost nothing but chocolate cake for weeks after John Lennon was killed.</em></p>

<p><em>Here&rsquo;s a box of our best: some of the most interesting words we&rsquo;ve printed about love and relationship over the past eight years &mdash; some of it&rsquo;s nutty, some of it&rsquo;s bittersweet, maybe you&rsquo;ll find the cherry.</em></p>

<p><em>Why a </em><strong>SUN</strong><em> Valentine on Love and Relationship? Because it&rsquo;s almost all we&rsquo;ve been talking about around here. See my editor&rsquo;s note (inside cover). See the faces of my friends.</em></p>

<p><em>Help yourself.</em></p>

<p class="text-right"><em>&mdash; Ed.</em></p>

<hr />
<p><em>People need a little loving and, God, sometimes it&rsquo;s sad all the shit they have to go through to find some.</em></p>

<p class="text-right">Richard Brautigan</p>

<p><em>All you hear from guys is desire, desire, desire, knocking its way out of the breast, and fear, striking and striking. Enough already! Time for a word of truth. Time for something notable to be heard. Otherwise, accelerating like a stone, you fall from life to death. Exactly like a stone, straight into deafness, and till the last repeating </em>I want I want I want<em>, then striking the earth and entering it forever!</em></p>

<p class="text-right">Saul Bellow<br />
<em>Henderson The Rain King</em></p>

<p><em>The heat inside the human body grows, it does not know where to throw itself &mdash; for a while it knots into will, heavy, burning, sweet, then into generosity, that longs to take on the burdens of others, then into mad love that lasts forever.</em></p>

<p class="text-right">Robert Bly<br />
<em>The Body Is Made of Camphor and Gopherwood</em></p>

<p><strong>An Interview With Robert Bly</strong></p>

<p>Everyone has two relationships. If I am a man, I have a relationship with a woman, or women; and then I have a relationship with my interior woman. One becomes a model for the other. We have a role model; and the way you relate to your interior woman probably decides how you will behave with other women.</p>

<p>The woman is in a similar situation. If she despises her interior male she will find herself constantly attacking the outward male side in feminist groups. Her hostility to outward males means that she will probably never establish a decent relationship with her own male side. So something is going wrong here in the way the women&rsquo;s movement has turned more and more to attacking males. Because all they are doing are tearing themselves to pieces. If you understand that no one is completely female and no one is completely male, it has to be. So from that point of view the whole matter is more complicated than I felt in the beginning; and I think one has to be very careful to avoid the constant attack on males or females once you understand that each is inside us.</p>

<p>Probably men have to develop their female sides if they want to become a <em>grown</em> man. I feel Lincoln was a grown man, Nixon was merely a male. Apparently, women have to develop their male side if they want to become a <em>grown</em> woman. It&rsquo;s said that three of the generals that Caesar faced were women. In the old Celtic civilization, there were many grown women. I&rsquo;ve recently become aware that it&rsquo;s important also which side is developed first. I think a man needs to develop his male side first, and after that it is time to develop the female side. Now, there are many cases in the sixties when boys in their twenties, because inside they were rejecting male consciousness along with Vietnam involvement, tried to develop their female side first. And they became babysitters before they became men. They became bakers of brown bread before they had actually developed their male consciousness. How you want to interpret &ldquo;the male side&rdquo; is all up to you. But it seems to me that in ancient life the emphasis for men was on developing the male side and then the female side, in that order. Many women, I think, hesitate to go to law school at twenty because they feel a danger that they may lose touch with their own feminine side. That&rsquo;s right. In a culture like ours in which woman is not really respected, many women are already out of touch with their woman side. If they ignore that and attempt to go forward and develop the male then they begin to deny any of the distinction between male and female. What is missing in our culture for women involves really respecting what is womanly and basing, grounding yourself in that. That means not so much to be feminine, but womanly, taking life seriously.</p>

<hr />
<p><em>Sometimes it seems to me that in this absurdly random life there is some inherent justice in the outcome of personal relationships. In the long run, we get no more than we have been willing to risk giving.</em></p>

<p class="text-right">Sheldon Kopp<br />
<em>If You Meet The Buddha On The Rood, Kill Him</em></p>

<p><em>Using another as a means of satisfaction and security is not love. Love is never security; love is a state in which there is no desire to be secure; it is a state of vulnerability.</em></p>

<p class="text-right">J. Krishnamurti</p>

<p><em>Love is when I am concerned with your relationship with your own life, rather than with your relationship to mine.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;. There must be a commitment to each other&rsquo;s well-being. Most people who say they have a commitment don&rsquo;t; they have an attachment. Commitment means, &ldquo;I am going to stick with you and support your experience of well-being.&rdquo; Attachment means, &ldquo;I am stuck without you.&rdquo;</em></p>

<p class="text-right">Stewart Emery</p>

<hr />
<p class="text-center"><strong>Friends</strong></p>

<p>.&nbsp;.&nbsp;. The most important rule I have in sexual etiquette is: Never make love to a friend of a friend. There are other rules, like not having a sexual relationship with employees or people you work with, or your neighbors, and there are very clear reasons for those things. But the most important one involves the close friend &mdash; or lover, for that matter &mdash; of one of your friends. The reason is very straightforward: If you were my close friend, or my lover, and you had a very close friend who seemed to be interested in me, or in whom I was interested, if I were to follow through with that interest it might put our friendship in jeopardy. Most sexual relationships have a high probability of frustration; high meaning maybe 25% of the people who become sexual partners do not remain friends. There&rsquo;s something about the sexual relationship that increases the probability of friction. Not that the other 75% can&rsquo;t be wonderful and spectacular, but something like 25% of the time you can have some friction that&rsquo;s unwanted and unnecessary. The consequence of that is that it reflects back on your friendship, because then your close friend has some strong feeling against or about me. I realized long ago that sexual relations are much easier to come by than friends and therefore they should be given a lower priority. The friendship, because it&rsquo;s rarer and much more important in your life, should be given a higher priority.</p>

<p class="text-right"><em>Michael Phillips</em></p>

<p><strong>An Interview<br />
With William Irwin Thompson</strong></p>

<p><span class="interviewee-er">SUN:</span> In California also, one out of every two marriages ends in divorce.</p>

<p><span class="interviewee-er">Thompson:</span> Well, that&rsquo;s also becoming true in parts of America outside of California. We&rsquo;re clearly in an unstable area where marriages break up. But you know, if you look at your friends, especially maybe at my age, 41, you find the pattern happening that after marraiges break up, and a person may spend a period time in relationships, sooner or later either one or both get married again. Partly because people get bored with the kind of Annie Hall date where you go out and talk about relationships all the time, because it&rsquo;s a bore to date a woman and hear her talk about nothing except her last relationships and her previous boyfriends and her this and her that. And so after that boredom when you find someone who can share a sense of value and share a life&rsquo;s work, and be involved in it, you tend to get mated. Now maybe these matings won&rsquo;t last for a long time. I remember once seeing a film on the day books of Edward Weston. He said that at every chapter of his life a different woman came in and that at every spiritual turning and major revolution in his heart, the woman changed. Now this could easily be said as much for a woman as for a man. But maybe what we are seeing as we go through many incarnations &mdash; almost in one lifetime now &mdash; you may start out as a lawyer, you may decide to drop out or you start as a professor and you drop out of that. You can&rsquo;t stay in the same relationship for your entire life. That&rsquo;s fine. The difficulty is, of course, what happens to the kids. And we haven&rsquo;t worked that one out. It&rsquo;s a real toughie. I&rsquo;ve had to deal with it in terms of my own life, trying to really keep involved with my kids, even though one of my children doesn&rsquo;t live with me. No easy answers to any of that. It&rsquo;s all very painful stuff. And where it&rsquo;s going, it&rsquo;s hard to say. But I don&rsquo;t think it&rsquo;s going to entropy. I think it&rsquo;s going to stabilize into new forms.</p>

<h5 class="text-center">Together</h5>

<pre class="text-indent"><span class="poem-line">I want to love loneliness</span>
<span class="poem-line">the way I love you. I want</span>
<span class="poem-line">to enter it and twist up its</span>
<span class="poem-line">hair in my fist. Its mouth open</span>
<span class="poem-line">like the sea. My thoughts like</span>
<span class="poem-line">bandages peeling away. Breathing</span>
<span class="poem-line">together, my loneliness and I.</span></pre>

<p class="text-right"><em>Sy Safransky</em></p>

<p class="text-center"><strong>Marriage: More Than A Twosome</strong></p>

<p>Marriage is an organizing principle, order brought to bear upon chaos, the complications of two against the complexity of one. It is a coordination, &ldquo;coordinate&rdquo; meaning &ldquo;of equal rank,&rdquo; a protean and perseverant form.</p>

<p>The word for &ldquo;single, alone&rdquo; &mdash; monos &mdash; is related to the words for &ldquo;to lack&rdquo; and &ldquo;sparse.&rdquo; There are benefits to be had from sparseness, from solitude, from being with oneself. The question is whether, in any given person, this signifies a deficiency of being.</p>

<p>A twosome is a complementary endeavor. A threesome is more stable yet, suggesting completion. Marriage provides the third corner to a twosome and stabilizes it into the unit of our biology and culture. A child from marriage transforms a metaphorical triad into a physical one: thus is family generated.</p>

<p>And yet there is a sense in which a marriage is itself family, is progeny of the two. The marriage is an entity or energy which comes from a combination of beings, giving them ballast and balance.</p>

<p>A twosome without marriage lacks this provision, and is that much less secure, standing on two pivot points, must be supplied with that many more accompaniments &mdash; of gesture, vocabulary, and social riddles. It tends not to have such firm footing or endurance.</p>

<p>Marriage does not survive in many twosomes because the number of elements is tripled, not doupled as they may suppose. There is me, you, and us. Therefore, there must be skills of autonomy, relationship, and of creation. Self, other, and that whole which is greater than the mere sum of its parts. A decreasing number of people bring such skills, or the ability to develop them, to each other. There are more and more twosomes masquerading as marriages.</p>

<p class="text-right"><em>Hal Lenke</em></p>

<hr />
<p><em>It is possible to imagine a more generous enclosure &mdash; a household welcoming to neighbors and friends: a garden open to the weather, between the woods and the road. It is possible to imagine a marriage bond that would bind a woman and a man not only to each other, but to the community of marriage, the amorous communion at which all couples sit: the sexual feast and celebration that joins them to all living things and to the fertility of the earth, and the sexual responsibility that joins them to the human past and the human future. It is possible to imagine marriage as a grievous, joyous human bond, endlessly renewable and renewing, again and again rejoining memory and passion and hope.</em></p>

<p class="text-right">Wendell Berry<br />
The Unsettling of America</p>

<h5 class="text-center">A Marriage</h5>

