<p class="text-center"><strong>Letter To A Brother</strong></p>

<p>Dear __________,</p>

<p>I probably would be too sensible to write this normally, but there is very little normal in my life these days. I realize I&rsquo;m not taking much responsibility for your feelings doing this, but that&rsquo;s good for me. Hope it&rsquo;s good for you, too.</p>

<p>Don&rsquo;t ever again talk to me about marriage. It is ultimately bad for your cause, if nothing else, because it seems so ungrounded in the landscape of essential emotion. You begin to look like a person contemplating a smorgasbord of LIFE/WOMEN and lighting on me as the most succulent peach. OK, I am, I&rsquo;m a winner, I&rsquo;m the moon, but the moon is Buddha. I guess I&rsquo;m telling you that I have a lot of disrespect for what I perceive as greed in your love.</p>

<p>I don&rsquo;t feel comfortable being defined as the woman who means one woman to you. It&rsquo;s not reciprocal &mdash; when I feel that way about someone, he&rsquo;s usually very yang, to kick off the yin echo in me. That&rsquo;s never been the energy dynamic between us. Ruthless and nasty as this may seem, it feels like a motion towards truth on my part and even the most difficult truth is better than the most delicious of lies.</p>

<p>We&rsquo;ve had some delicious times that weren&rsquo;t lies. I don&rsquo;t want to deny the good stuff, but I am really angry at you. Some big blind spot keeps you from respecting something in me that requires your respect or I will hate you. You will violate me again, and again I will get pregnant, I will have abortion after abortion.</p>

<p>Give it up. I am here, your sister, someone else who has fought past the bankers of souls to songs and words that dance, I will help you in your growth, your struggle whichever way I can, but you&rsquo;ve got to give it up, the thing you are doing relative to me. I hate it. I hold hands with you, it&rsquo;s warm and sweet, we wade into it, my smile congeals over teeth, icy teeth. I guess I&rsquo;m warning you. Don&rsquo;t come near me with your projection, ever again. Give me my wholeness, it will help you find your own.</p>

<p>To mail this? Or fade into safety and distance. I&rsquo;m not sure. Maybe it will end up to be more healing than harmful. You will survive it, I will respect you for surviving it. Where is your own anger? Write me a letter.</p>

<p>Not two.</p>

