<p class="text-center"><strong>Exquisite Relationship</strong></p>

<p>That&rsquo;s the secret of exquisite relationship, by the way. It&rsquo;s when the two people use truth as a vehicle to come into a relationship in which it has gone beyond a relationship because there is only one of it playing that it&rsquo;s two. And even when the two are locked in the worst nitty-grittiness &mdash; &ldquo;I hate your guts! You&rsquo;ve done this to me, I&rsquo;ve been with you too long&rdquo; &mdash; even at that moment there is this little whisper across the top, &ldquo;You still here? I&rsquo;m still here. Far-out! God, this is heavy!&rdquo; As long as you are serious in your own story line, as long as you are who you think you are, you are really quite mechanical. You are determined. You are karmic run-off. But the minute that next plane of awareness starts, your karmic run-off just became relatively real, not absolutely real. Then you just keep adding plane after plane after plane. And then you&rsquo;re just living out your drama. But through that comes absolute light because there&rsquo;s nothing that narrows the pipe on the way through, because there&rsquo;s nobody holding on anywhere. There is total involvement and no attachment. You are an environment in which anybody else &mdash; whether it&rsquo;s your child, your spouse, your boss, your employee, your bus-driver, whoever &mdash; can be with you as one, if they choose. And if they don&rsquo;t, if they are busy holding onto their separateness, it is perfectly OK because you don&rsquo;t need them to recognize the fact that we are both God.</p>

<p class="text-right"><em>Ram Dass</em></p>

<p class="text-center"><strong>The Dark Mother</strong></p>

<p>As an infant in your dependence you trust, and in a sense crave, the female to be beneficent, because of the helplessness. The mother is, in general, the nourisher. But the female, as well as the male, also has a negative side. To a male child the negative side of the mother is the darkest, scariest thing he can perceive. What could be scarier than that? A bunch of scary warriors coming through would be rationally acceptable &mdash; they&rsquo;re not your mother, at least.</p>

<p>So a woman who, of her own nature, has a dark side &mdash; she will also be creative. Something is triggered by being a witness to that most paradoxical of human situations, witnessing the dark and light side of the mother simultaneously. Most people only witness the light side of the mother. Literally. They only see the bright side of the mother, in one way or another. But some people see the <strong>dark</strong> side of the mother. If you only see the dark side you probably go crazy. The poet holds the dark and the light in mind, together. Which, by extension, means birth and death in its totality. We worship not only the positive forces, the life-giving forces &mdash; not just that. We can all say, &ldquo;Ah, planet earth biosphere, mother earth, mother wonderful &mdash; all these green plants.&rdquo; But there&rsquo;s also death, there&rsquo;s also the unknown, there&rsquo;s also the demonic. And that&rsquo;s the womb and the tomb, that&rsquo;s samsara, that&rsquo;s birth and death, that&rsquo;s where the Buddhists go in. And that&rsquo;s where poetry goes in: That&rsquo;s where poetry gets its hands on something real. And it is triggered, I think &mdash; in many people I know it is triggered by seeing that in their infancy as a condition of the universe in the psychology of their own life.</p>

<p class="text-right"><em>Gary Snyder</em></p>

