<hr />
<p class="text-center"><strong>An Interview With Jehangir Chubb</strong></p>

<p><span class="interviewee-er">SUN:</span> What does love mean to you, and how does and doesn&rsquo;t it relate to romantic love?</p>

<p><span class="interviewee-er">CHUBB:</span> I think that spiritual love, which is a total self-giving without any thought of return, is the true nature of love. Then it may take a different form when, as it were, it enters into a restricted field of consciousness. There it may become romantic love. And it still retains its value in that particular expression. It is only when romantic love becomes possessive and thoughtless that there is degradation and distortion. So romantic love can be a very helpful thing, even in one&rsquo;s spiritual life, if the two people help each other to grow. But that should not degenerate into possessive love, where you become all-important. Then love turns into a form of exploitation.</p>

<p><span class="interviewee-er">SUN:</span> From your observations, how many people in romantic relationships are able to manifest that more spiritual love?</p>

<p><span class="interviewee-er">CHUBB:</span> Well, it happens in India, we have that tradition there; if the two partners are both spiritually inclined, they help each other. Many of our sages have said the same thing, that such a relation can very helpful indeed. But love in itself is its own eternity. It doesn&rsquo;t require any response from anybody else to sustain itself.</p>

<p><span class="interviewee-er">SUN:</span> So the beloved is all existence; one doesn&rsquo;t need a single object. In fact, in having a single object, love can turn into something other than love.</p>

<p><span class="interviewee-er">CHUBB:</span> Not other than love. I think that the qualities which we regard as values &mdash; love is one of them &mdash; exist in their absolute form in themselves or in the Divine and they can manifest under conditions of relative existence, where love, to take one quality, doesn&rsquo;t cease to be love but becomes a lower and diminished form of the absolute quality. This is because there is an analogical resemblance between human qualities and their divine equivalents and this justifies us in using the same word: love, wisdom, knowledge, power. But the divine quality is quantitatively different from the human quality. It is not merely a higher degree of the corresponding human quality. When we pass from the human to the divine quality something new comes into being, something incomparable and ineffable. So romantic love is still love. We don&rsquo;t need to use another word.</p>

<p><span class="interviewee-er">SUN:</span> If the romantic love we&rsquo;re absorbed in is not the same as the deeper spiritual love we would like to feel, what do we do about that predicament?</p>

<p><span class="interviewee-er">CHUBB:</span> Why should it be a predicament? These things are permissable in the sense that they are helpful, in their own way. So why should it create a problem? The predicament would be artificial: I want to love in a spiritual way, but I don&rsquo;t. Now that is an artificial demand.</p>

<p><span class="interviewee-er">SUN:</span> How is it artificial?</p>

<p><span class="interviewee-er">CHUBB:</span> Because you are setting up this ideal of spiritual love and saying this is what I must achieve. But according to the Buddha all growth should be spontaneous and natural. You don&rsquo;t set up an ideal of what you want to be and try to become it. You become aware of what you are, and in that very process you become or realize the ideal.</p>

<p class="text-center"><strong>Kali Comes Home</strong></p>

<p>It is Kali come home, this territory. Kali &mdash; the ancient Hindu goddess of Destruction, sweet hurricane horror with single purpose: to sweep away delusions. I know this place all too well, but it remains an unfamiliar passage, even in its predictability, in the fierceness of the fire, as Kali matches tit for tat, attacks self-seriousness in any form, even under the most tragic of circumstances. She comes in drag, wearing a heavy cloak of despair, every imagined loss a looming reality in the fragmented darkness of her eyes.</p>

<p>The truth is forgotten, I am a blind woman on my hands and knees, fingertips following the silk thread through the dark, heart in its season of sorrow, crying &ldquo;If only&rsquo;s&rdquo; and every regret, every denial, hating the moment because I think the light is lost, the beloved gone forever, my confusion the damnation I will be remembered by. It is a short-term hurt for a long-term heal; I suddenly understand, not through some feat of logic but through living alone with the only thing I have ever had or will ever have &mdash; the pearl of my Isness. I am not alone, I am the beloved, I am understood, and there is nothing I need ever change.</p>

<p>Starving dog that I am, I refuse to accept the Kali kiss until each time my radar confirms from every satellite signal: yes, this is the way, I can detect no loss, anywhere, in this allowance for everything.</p>

<p>Friends, mates, parents, siblings are separate planets within a larger united universe, not responsible for fulfilling my fantasies of how we meet, or even acknowledging the bridges are there.</p>

<p class="text-right"><em>Elizabeth Rose Campbell</em></p>

<hr />
<p><em>To marry a woman with any success a man must have a total experience of her, he must come to see her and accept her in time as well as in space. Besides coming to love through attraction what she is now, he must also come to realize and love equally the baby and the child she once was, and the middle-aged woman and the old crone she will eventually become .&nbsp;.&nbsp;.</em></p>

<p class="text-right">James Keyes<br />
<em>Only Two Can Play This Game</em></p>

<hr />
<p class="text-center"><strong>Going To God</strong></p>

<p>To us, marriage is only a vehicle for going to God. Monks go solo, and married couples go as a tag-team; one can&rsquo;t get even a step ahead at the other&rsquo;s expense. If the couple truly becomes &ldquo;Dharma-mates&rdquo; then there is never the question of separation or divorce. This Dharma marriage is quite different from a marriage based on social/psychological principles such as peace, happiness, liberated woman, liberated man in the popular sense. The Dharma marriage is a raw, no-holds-barred journey in which neither partner has any &ldquo;rights&rdquo; at all or spaces to uphold and protect, etc. Ram Dass used to query us, &ldquo;Do you want to be right, or do you want to be free?&rdquo;</p>

<p>Rather than developing a context which maximizes the daily peace and harmony, the Dharma marriage equally fulfills the function of showing both partners all their uptightness, weaknesses and insecurities so that they can become free rather than just comfortable. Many marriages in our culture dissolve because the discomfort becomes too great for our model of what marriage should be like. Ironically, there&rsquo;s tremendous joy in giving up even the slightest model or anxiety about having a happy marriage. There&rsquo;s an old Buddhist saying, &ldquo;Ah, the joy, to discover that there&rsquo;s no happiness to be found in this world.&rdquo;</p>

<p>If I want to be free, then anything that Sita does that gets me uptight is simply one more opportunity for me; it has nothing at all to do with her. If our life together is pleasant, that&rsquo;s fine; if it&rsquo;s not, then that&rsquo;s fine too. Our union is a precious opportunity to come to God; who else other than your wife or husband can pick apart all those deepest, subtlest ego spaces? Why give that up so that we can hide better? In a sense this is the difference between <em>bond</em> and <em>relationship</em>. Sita and I have a stronger bond every day, <em>because</em> our relationship dissolves more every day. Relationship implies specified ways or guidelines within which two people deal with each other; agreements, more or less, about what goes and what doesn&rsquo;t. The more defined a relationship, the less the union can evolve and change; the two people only have a certain context with each other; there&rsquo;s a built-in stress in the system right from day one. The less the relationship, it&rsquo;s a littles scarier, but the stronger is the bond which develops. One year may be filled with romance, the next year may be totally platonic, in a third they may seemingly be going in different directions, in a fourth they may be driving each other crazy. The Dharma-mates don&rsquo;t freak as their space changes, because they&rsquo;re not clinging to a model of how it should be. It all becomes fascinating to experience &mdash; quite humbling as well. The Love deepens and grows too much to remain personal, and becomes Love for God instead. There&rsquo;s no husband or wife, just two intimately connected beings becoming free together; for thousands and thousands of year, crossing gender and cultures and times .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. Change comes only with time; and Love defeats time. A relationship which depends on certain things changing or not changing is not one in Love.</p>

<p>Children become part of the marriage. The husband-wife-children thing is just the brief passing support system this time around. We honor that level, but also live more as two brothers and a sister on the spiritual journey. Laxmana, Sita and I are a marriage which we enjoy and appreciate more than words can describe. One of the definitions of &ldquo;marriage&rdquo; is &ldquo;an intimate union.&rdquo; In answer to your question, &ldquo;What is marriage?&rdquo;, it certainly is an intimate Yoga &mdash; one intricate, exquisite vehicle for going to God.</p>

<p>Ah, the grand humor of it all .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. Here comes the wind, the warm dry night wind, and who are we .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. ?</p>

<p class="text-right"><em>Bo, Sita, and Laxmana Lozoff</em></p>

<p class="text-center"><strong>The Aquarian Age</strong></p>

<p>Aquarius, needless to say, can be hard on marriage. In fact, we can look at marriage as a microcosm of this whole cycle of ages. Marriage is a coupling; it arises from the urge to find our complement, our other half, in another person. This is an archetypal human quality. It will persist; as long as there is a sexual polarity there will be a coupling instinct. But that coupling instinct can be manifested in countless ways. Under Pisces, we see the urge to dissolve the self into a greater whole and, in this case, to dissolve the self into the unit of a couple. Under Aquarius, we don&rsquo;t find an end to love, or an end to sexual polarity but we do find an entirely new basis for being a couple. The couple as a unit into which we dissolve ourselves is over. That finished with the Piscean age. Under Aquarius we find still the basic hunger to seek the other half but also much more emphasis upon individuality and the autonomy of each partner.</p>

<p>We see the skyrocketing divorce rate in this century. There are the usual complaints of cruelty, adultery, abandonment. But we find a new theme in marriages that collapse: &ldquo;I needed more freedom. I needed more independence. I couldn&rsquo;t find myself in this marriage.&rdquo; This is much more than a passing whim of our culture. This, too, is part of that archetypal energy that is being set into motion, and will be working itself out for next two thousand years. While it does not mean the end of marriage, it definitely will lead to its radical restructuring. We are no longer going to worship longevity in a marriage. We will worship individual growth within it. We will no longer fall under the Piscean myth that in marriage you may hate each other but if you just stay together you&rsquo;re a big success. That&rsquo;s Pisces: &ldquo;I have dissolved myself into a greater whole.&rdquo; It is not true of Aquarius. Successful marraiges may occur in shorter periods, packing the evolution of a lifetime into five years. You get two strong individuals together and sparks fly. Everybody on the Earth wants to be a stronger individual under the Aquarian energy. Under Pisces, we would drift, we would lose ourselves. That is no longer appropriate. It&rsquo;s not that one is better than the other, or harder than the other. It&rsquo;s that they are different methods of learning and we are ready for a new one. Marriage will take on a wide array of new forms as we move into the Aquarian pattern.</p>

<p>We will recognize a couple as a couple even though they live apart. We&rsquo;ll also find periods of separation in the marriage becoming more acceptable. One person will say, &ldquo;I love you but I need to go to Europe for the next six months. You&rsquo;re beginning to get on my nerves. If I don&rsquo;t leave, we&rsquo;re going to stop loving each other.&rdquo; This will be acceptable even to conservative people in 100 years. In the Piscean age, separation meant the marriage was on the edge of disaster. In the Aquarian age we are going to find men and women who become entangled with each other for their entire lifetimes but in isolated units of time. They&rsquo;ll be together when they&rsquo;re in their twenties, when they&rsquo;re in their forties, when they&rsquo;re in their eighties. In their fifties, they&rsquo;ll be apart, but they&rsquo;re still a couple. We&rsquo;ll probably find more &ldquo;coupling&rdquo; units of three or four people. Again, I&rsquo;m not saying this is the archetypal pattern of the Eighties but just that we&rsquo;re moving into an age in which there will be much more freedom for individual expression and this will be reflected within the socially acceptable forms of marriage.</p>

<p>The dangerous side of this is the selfishness that can so easily arise. All through history, love has been the only force that gets anybody any higher. Love has to contain a certain amount of compromise. Under Aquarius we&rsquo;ll find more people throwing the baby out with the bath water. Relationships will be more likely to break up over some minor issue. In the past, that was unthinkable. Couples would stay together in the face of any problem. Under Aquarius, it&rsquo;s the old &ldquo;I like to sleep with the window open and you sleep with the window closed.&rdquo; And that was the end of the relationship. This is an Aquarian sentiment. It&rsquo;s not healthy. Commitment to another person is going to take on a deeper kind of poignancy. For one, it&rsquo;s going to be much harder. The sense of freedom, the sense of separation, will be so strong that to say, &ldquo;I love you and I respect you, and my life&rsquo;s scheme is bound up in your life&rsquo;s scheme as long as we live,&rdquo; will really be a mouthful. In the Piscean age it was easy to do that; not now. The relationships that endure, marriages that endure, will be the most dynamic marriages that have ever existed.</p>

<p class="text-right"><em>Steven Forrest</em></p>

<hr />
<p><em>Marriage is not a matter of creating a quick community of spirit by tearing down and destroying all boundaries, but rather a good marriage is that in which each appoints the other guardian of his solitude .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. Once the realization is accepted that even between the closest human beings infinite distances continue to exist, a wonderful living side by side can grow up, if they succeed in loving the distance between them no less than one another.</em></p>

<p class="text-right">Rilke</p>

<hr />
<p class="text-center"><strong>An Interview With Ram Dass</strong></p>

<p>But when I <em>intentionally</em> go into a relationship, it&rsquo;s primarily designed for liberation. If I&rsquo;m in a relationship with somebody and we get lost in a drama, in our habitual responses, all I&rsquo;m doing is increasing his suffering. I&rsquo;m not liberating him. All I can do for him is to become free, because my freedom helps him become free. If I&rsquo;m trapped, he gets trapped too. So, it sounds callous but it&rsquo;s the most compassionate thing I can do. I mean, the worst thing is to be kind to somebody, in a way that makes him an object: I don&rsquo;t want to tell him this because it would hurt him or I don&rsquo;t feel like I&rsquo;m growing but I&rsquo;ll be kind. Those kind of relationships, in the long run, are more corrosive to human dignity and human liberation and to the end of suffering, although that&rsquo;s mostly what we do in relationships. We&rsquo;re very kind with each other. But I find that truth, which is fiercer, is often kinder in a more profound sense. I&rsquo;m not saying this very well. But I know what I&rsquo;m trying to say.</p>

<p>In the relationship I&rsquo;ve been in, I got to the point where I felt &ldquo;we&rsquo;ve gone as far as we can go&rdquo; and then said to him, &ldquo;I think we&rsquo;ve gone as far as we can go.&rdquo; And that&rsquo;s been a catalyst for us to open to another place and start to go deeper. But it&rsquo;s painful to say that because it&rsquo;s scary. You&rsquo;re jeopardizing the whole thing. You&rsquo;d better be willing to risk the end all the time, to have the new beginning. You&rsquo;ve got to keep risking it all. Saying that if it doesn&rsquo;t liberate me, I don&rsquo;t want to be in it means I don&rsquo;t want to be just two personalities locked together. I want to be two manifestations of God, dancing together. Which is a liberated relationship. It&rsquo;s a relationship where there&rsquo;s one dancing as two, not two locked in their separateness. To me, the prison of two people locked in their own separateness, which is being together out of habit or out of kindness, is just too horrible.</p>

<p>There is a tremendous amount of separateness and fear that leads people to settle for living an interesting kind of hell of the comfort of familiarity, but no living spirit. I used to travel in my van and I&rsquo;d often be in places where there were a lot of motor homes of retired people. And you would watch the relationships, talk to people and have a drink with them and play with their pets. And you could sense often these walking mechanical scenes. It&rsquo;s like old shoes, they&rsquo;re comfortable, but there&rsquo;s nothing living happening. It&rsquo;s presumptuous to say, except, as I get deeper in as a therapist with people, I feel that. It&rsquo;s like sleep-walking until it&rsquo;s all over. There&rsquo;s a kind of ghastliness about that. That&rsquo;s very common. We are all prone to it because we are a certain pay-off and we don&rsquo;t want to risk going broke. We&rsquo;ll settle for 22 percent rather than going for even 30 percent. And we settle very quickly. <em>Very</em> quickly. I watched us do it. It&rsquo;s not enough.</p>

<hr />
<p><em>I say you shall yet find the friend you were looking for.</em></p>

<p class="text-right">Walt Whitman</p>

<hr />
<p class="text-center"><strong>Patricia Sun On Men and Women</strong></p>

<p>There&rsquo;s a tremendous amount of programming and conditioning that is almost biologically oriented in the way that we happen to be born. In this duality of either/or thinking, there&rsquo;s one extremely lopsided thing that happens. And that is that every single human being who exists has been born only of a female body, has lived parasitically off the flesh of that body, inside of that body, for about nine months, and then for most of humanity&rsquo;s history, off of that body for a year or two or three or four more. For something of an animal body in a four-square reality, that is powerful stuff. You don&rsquo;t live if Mom doesn&rsquo;t let you grow in her body, or take care of you afterwards. Plus, in duality thinking, if someone has the power of life, they then, of course, have the power of death. Stop to think what this does as a set-up for men. Because, while women certainly get programmed with a ton of junk, on that particular issue, whether they have children or not, they know: &ldquo;Oh, my body is one of those.&rdquo; &ldquo;Oh yeah, I&rsquo;m one of those, like Mom.&rdquo; So with women, for whatever your hassle is, whatever your fears are, whatever your dilemmas, whatever programming you have to work out, you at least have the &ldquo;I&rsquo;m one of those&rdquo; identification.</p>

<p>But for men, it remains always an otherness power. When you are strictly four-square reality thinking, that&rsquo;s something else, and that&rsquo;s why throughout human history, women were, in pre-recorded history, dominant, and had to give it up because the men&rsquo;s terror was too great; and they became submissive, and owned by men. Then, it was the father owned the daughter, and handed her over to the husband, and there was the virginity thing so that nobody else got in there to tap that power.</p>

<p>Where did all that craziness come from in our cultures? We treat it like &ldquo;well, that&rsquo;s just life.&rdquo; The fact that we come in two kinds of bodies and only one kind grows new life has a profound hookup to consciousness evolving, and to the nature of the duality plane, and the nature of our trying to comprehend it.</p>

<p>Now there&rsquo;s also a biological thing of women feeling very &ldquo;at effect&rdquo; of their bodies. Giving birth often meant death, it certainly meant hardship, and you were extremely vulnerable for a long period of time. That set up one of the big programmings and conditionings that women have &mdash; they need to own men, to get them to take care of them. &ldquo;You need to have a man. You need to get married.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&rdquo; All those imageries come from the same biological thing from the time we were running away from saber-toothed tigers. The fact is that we no longer need to do that. That&rsquo;s not here anymore. Now we&rsquo;re here to connect. To use what we&rsquo;ve each learned. To share feelings. To get to sense the other person, to break down that barrier of fear.</p>

<p>Once I was with a few women at a picnic dinner at somebody&rsquo;s house; the guys were out playing volleyball, the ladies were inside talking. And they were all talking about the men. They were all being very lucid, very clear, very accurate, and very complete in their understanding of how those men were, what their relationships were, what the problems were. They were very clear. And I thought,&ldquo;Wow, these ladies really have good relationships.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Then the men came in. And the women who&rsquo;d been speaking very clearly suddenly went (laughs embarrassedly). And everything went iiicchhhhkkk. It was like a wave that went across the room, and the men felt it, and then their reaction to that yuck was to get yucky the other way, and then there was this ooh, in the room, and I thought. &ldquo;Oh my God, that&rsquo;s what it is. Men are terrified of women. And women are terrified of letting men know they know they&rsquo;re terrified.&rdquo;</p>

<p>And that&rsquo;s the why to all this crazy song and dance we do. And why women are terrified is because throughout history they&rsquo;ve gotten murdered a lot whenever they&rsquo;d say what they thought or used men&rsquo;s fear. When you get that imprinted in your genetic memory, you get very evasive.</p>

<p>So it&rsquo;s been the way we&rsquo;ve done the dance, to figure out who we are. All of this hasn&rsquo;t needed to be happening for a long time, and it&rsquo;s the hangover of the unconsciousness of the energy, not really founded in the realities of survival except as we create self-fulfilling prophecy. What we&rsquo;re about to do is really look at how we have these unfinished experiences .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. it&rsquo;s the real meaning behind ancestor worship. You must respect your heritage. Not in an exclusive sense of being better than anybody else, but in knowing that all your ancestors have been working on different pieces, and you&rsquo;ve got assorted little vulgarities left over programmed into you that you have to become aware of and straighten out. And bring your consciousness into freedom, bring it into light. Bring it out of the shadow.</p>
														</div>


				
